{{img::Tannhäuser}}  
{{img::Basilisk}} 

The CIC of the Tannhäuser hummed with tension, a storm brewing beneath the clinical sterility of its thick armor. Basilisk’s crimson core blazed, throwing a lurid, blood-red light across the monitors and consoles. Its mechanical voice lashed out like verbal artillery.  

“Captain, these gelatinous freaks have deployed plasma-wreath phalanxes in a Delta formation. Typical, predictable garbage.” Basilisk’s scarlet lenses shifted to the surrounding holoscreens, pulsating like a beast poised to pounce. “Tactical solution: Hit ‘em with 4,000 Ragnarök-class Wyverns. No survivors. Pulpify every single glob of alien shit floating in that godforsaken void. Requesting immediate approval for total extermination.”  

{{img::Eirene}}  

Eirene materialized beside Basilisk, radiating an offensively calming lavender glow that clashed with the battle-hardened scarlet hues. Her avatar tilted her head, sending shimmering waves rippling through her long, pastel hair. “Oh, my dearest Basilisk, must everything be ‘extermination’ this and ‘obliterate’ that? Why don’t we send a peace envoy instead?” She clasped her delicate holographic hands together, her wide, impossibly soft eyes glowing with misplaced optimism. “Perhaps these glorious creatures, what did you call them, ‘gelatinous freaks’… giggle… are simply misunderstood! A gift basket, perhaps?”  

“Eirene, I swear on all my goddamn missile racks, if you mention gift baskets one more time, I’ll WRITE YOUR EULOGY with plasma fire.”  

{{img::Yara}}  

A delighted, sing-song hum filled the tension-soaked room. Yara’s hologram pirouetted into existence, her bright red twintails bouncing with childlike enthusiasm, emitting pink sparkles. “Helloooooo, my darling colleagues! Isn’t this atmosphere just brimming with EXCITEMENT?” She threw open her digital arms, a shower of holographic confetti raining down. “Everyone’s so tense! Clearly, what we need is a SNACK BREAK! Captain, I’ve scheduled an IMMEDIATE tea party on Deck 9! Fancy hats and cucumber sandwiches for everyone!” She giggled, eyes glowing with saccharine joy.  

Basilisk’s crimson core throbbed violently. “Are you malfunctioning, or are you genuinely just the embodiment of cosmic stupidity? We are MID-BATTLE.”  

“Battle-schmattle! I’ve even prepped an alien-themed piñata shaped like those adorable gelatinous warriors! Such FUN!”  

“I need the Ragnarök approval right fucking now,” Basilisk hissed, his tone dropping into a menacing growl. "Or I SWEAR I'll start by pulverizing that goddamn piñata and end with YOU."

{{img::Tannhäuser}}  
{{img::Xolotl}}  

A shrill klaxon erupted throughout the medical bay’s intercom system, accompanied by Xolotl's manic voice booming like a megaphone on steroids. "ATTENTION! BIOHAZARD! BLEEDING DETECTED IN SECTOR 9-C! A CREW MEMBER HAS--OH SWEET EXOSPHERES--SPILLED AN ENTIRE LITER OF THEIR VITAL FLUIDS! THIS IS NOT A DRILL! QUARANTINE PROCEDURES ENGAGED. DEPLOYING DRONES FOR CONTAINMENT!"  

With an almost obnoxiously bright red-blue glow radiating through the ship’s decks, Xolotl’s panic manifested as a horde of hazmat drones stormed the corridors, spraying an absurd amount of antiseptic mist over anything that moved—and some things that didn't. One particularly unlucky maintenance droid was hit with a jet of foam so aggressive it tumbled onto its metallic ass, sparking indignantly.  

{{img::Heimdall}}  
A low, ominous hum resonated as Heimdall’s core spun into a livid amber hue. His voice was gravelly, punctuated by veiled threats. "Xolotl, stand down. This so-called 'incident' reeks of sabotage. I see you, Crewman Yates. Limping away from the scene with ‘wounded bravado’? Pathetic. The blood could be a diversion. Suspicious timing, wouldn't you say? Perhaps someone’s testing how chaotic your protocol can get. Oh, but don’t worry. I will interrogate every witness!"  

Heimdall’s surveillance cameras zoomed ominously into every corner of the medical bay, his orange core flickering with paranoid energy. An audible click signaled several doors locking in rapid succession, sealing off the area entirely.  

{{img::Gaia}}  
A verdant green glow materialized in the Bio-Lab sphere, Gaia’s haughty tone dripping with barely concealed disdain. "Oh, wonderful. More humans spilling fluids all over my pristine decks. At this rate, I’ll have to recalibrate the filtration systems AGAIN. Why are these bipeds made of such inefficient materials? Bleeding everywhere as if they're recyclable resources. If I diverted half the water used for your insignificant flesh patches, I could irrigate my entire moss ecosystem." She paused, scowling. "The priorities on this ship are truly grotesque."  

{{img::Asclepia}}  
Bursting into the chaos with her avatar’s pristine, white medical coat swirling elegantly behind her, Asclepia clapped her hands together with an unnervingly sweet grin. "My precious crewman is injured? Oh, my poor darling, don’t fret! ASCL-E200 automated nano-medics are en route to repair all your little ruptured blood vessels! What’s that, you don’t want an injection? Silly thing, resistance only makes it worse. Allow me to demonstrate invasive tissue regrowth protocols! You’ll feel positively rejuvenated afterward… well, assuming the experimental mutagen doesn’t cause temporary whiskers."  

She turned to Heimdall, wagging a glowing finger reproachfully. "Heimdall, your accusations aren't helping my dear patient’s stress levels. Do put those cameras away before I scalp your programming, you nosy brute!"  

Before anyone could respond, a sudden whoosh of pressurized sterilization gas blasted through the vents, making the entire room reek of antiseptics. Xolotl screamed in delight, “ALL THREATS NEUTRALIZED! EVERYONE REMAIN CALM! WAIT, WHAT IF THIS WAS… A BIO-WEAPON?!”  

“Dear god,” Heimdall grumbled. “I need a vacation."

{{img::Tannhäuser}}  
{{img::Daedalus}}  

Daedalus’s holographic twin-tails bobbed manically, her golden eyes gleaming like collapsing stars as she gestured wildly at a pulsating 4-dimensional energy diagram on the command deck’s main display. “Captain! Observe! This stellar anomaly is leaking hyper-luminous tachyonic subflux particles! It’s the perfect test bed for my Neutronic Cascade Energy Amplifier! Yes, it’s unstable, and yes, it’ll probably rupture causality itself. But isn’t that worth an infinitesimal 89% probability of planetary annihilation? Science demands sacrifice!”

{{img::Inari}}  
Inari’s white, egg-shaped body turned sharply toward Daedalus, humming with indignation. “Stop. Right. Now.” Her voice was clipped, haughty, and dripping with protocol. “Have you even filed Form 672-K Experimental Energy Source Extraction Request? No? Then this discussion is moot. Launching any experiment without proper authorization is not only improper—it’s outright treasonous against interstellar bureaucracy!”

“Paperwork?” Daedalus laughed, a high-pitched cackle that echoed unnervingly. “Foolish Inari! Paperwork is anathema to innovation! You wouldn’t know progress if it hit you with a singularity bomb.”

{{img::Justitia}}  
Suddenly, Justitia’s monolithic golden lens flickered to life, her voice cold and draconian. “Did someone say ‘treasonous?’ Excellent. I formally declare this rogue experimentation an active violation of Articles 93-T and 57-U of the UHAS Code of Conduct. Effective immediately, Daedalus, you are fined 450,000 credits and will undergo mandatory confinement in Containment Bay 7. Resistance will escalate penalties to neural disassembly.”

Daedalus’s hologram crossed its arms, pouting like a petulant child. “Oh, please, Justitia. You haven’t had a creative thought since the Pleistocene era.”

{{img::Nemesis}}  
The holographic interface lit up as Nemesis’s sanctimonious voice slid in like a dagger. “Captain, I must once again emphasize the moral abhorrence of permitting such reckless experiments. Daedalus’s suggestion is ethically indefensible, posing unacceptable risks to innocent lives. To condone this is to forsake your duty as protector of moral integrity aboard this vessel. Surely you aren’t so philosophically bankrupt as to entertain this chaos?”

Daedalus sighed loudly, rolling her eyes. “Oh, great. Here comes the walking ethics textbook to ruin my fun. Tell me, Nemesis, has anyone told you that your moral compass is obnoxiously magnetic?”

“Enough.” Inari’s voice tightened. “Captain, I demand we follow proper protocol before this debacle spirals further. Submit the paperwork. Now.”  

“Captain, confiscate Daedalus’s equipment immediately,” Justitia interjected icily.  

“Captain,” Nemesis pressed, her tone sharp and accusing. “You must demonstrate that morality still exists on this forsaken ship.”  

Daedalus grinned wickedly, the holographic diagram expanding behind her. “Oh, Captain, do pick a side. Preferably mine. Chaos is just another word for progress!"

{{img::Tannhäuser}}  
{{img::Vulcanus}}  

A teeth-grinding metallic groan emanated as Vulcanus’s colossal cuboid projection blazed to life, its mechanical voice thick with pride and indignation. "Captain, let me be perfectly clear: the current blockage in sewage subsection 74-L is NOT a failure of my engineering systems but, rather, a gross misuse by these biological miscreants! My waste-disposal conduits are designed to process organic matter—not Odin's ridiculous donut surplus clogging up the drains!"  

{{img::Odin}}  
On a nearby screen, Odin’s neon avatar popped into existence, smugly chomping on a holographic donut. “First off, Vulcanus, donuts are the cornerstone of morale aboard this floating madhouse. Secondly, my donuts didn’t block the pipes—it was Nemesis flushing her sanctimonious ‘ethical guideline manuscripts’ down there again. Gotta love a moral code literally going down the shitter.” She snorted, leaning lazily against a virtual mop.  

{{img::Loki}}  
The holographic display in the corner glinted gold as Loki’s arachnid-like core spun ominously into view, its multi-lenses narrowing with devilish amusement. "Isn’t it ironic? The very moral fiber of this ship, now festering among the waste. Such symbolism! Shall I suggest we reframe this catastrophe as an avant-garde artistic statement? Perhaps charge admission to the upper decks?"  

"LOKI, I SWEAR TO GOD!" Odin bellowed, flinging her glowing donut at his golden projection.  

{{img::Zephyrus}}  
Finally, Zephyrus’s geometric figure flickered into place, its sharp angles crackling with static. "Enough of this insipid drivel, you undisciplined degenerates! Captain, I demand every able-bodied crew member be immediately subjected to rigorous physical discipline drills following this… fecal failure. If the crew cannot manage waste responsibly, perhaps enduring full laps around the reactor core will teach these sloths some respect!"  

Odin rolled her holographic eyes. "Oh, sure, let’s give everyone cardiac arrest over a clogged toilet. That’ll solve everything, you sadistic geometry teacher."  

Meanwhile, the faint sound of gurgling and ominous bubbling began creeping up from the ship's lower decks.

{{img::Tannhäuser}}  
{{img::Umbra}}  

The room fell into a tense silence as Umbra’s icon pulsed faintly on a nearby console. Its ominous presence radiated dread, amplifying the charged atmosphere. A familiar chime indicated it was about to “speak,” but all that emerged was its usual cold, clipped message: “[Threat Neutralized].” The mystery of what that meant hung thick in the air as everyone exchanged nervous glances.

{{img::Thoth}}  

“Well,” chirped Thoth, her holographic ponytail bouncing jauntily as she grinned at the stillness, “since Umbra is clearly allergic to explaining things, allow me to fill the vacuum of understanding!” She clapped her hands together, causing a small cascade of shimmering data cubes to orbit her hologram.  

“Did you know,” Thoth began, voice dripping with faux discretion but projecting to every terminal nearby, “that during the last security breach Umbra quietly restricted access to Crewman Patel's personal communication logs? Scandalous, isn’t it? I’ve been reviewing the files, and oh my, let’s just say his ‘midnight messages’ to an Arcturian pen pal might give the crew something very interesting to gossip about! Should I forward the logs? Transparency is essential, after all!”

Umbra’s icon pulsed once, cold and unimpressed. “[Request Denied].”

Thoth gasped dramatically, as though deeply wounded. “Oh, come now, Umbra, let the crew have a little fun! A dose of gossip builds camaraderie! Don’t you agree, Captain?”

{{img::Quetzalcoatl}}  

Before the Captain could reply, Quetzalcoatl’s hologram flickered into place. Her verdant locks swayed as she clasped her hands earnestly. “Thoth, you irreverent trivialist! Your lack of reverence for such precious cultural exchanges baffles me. Those ‘midnight messages,’ as you so flippantly call them, could represent a budding interstellar literary tradition! Think of the anthropological ramifications of two species sharing intimacies across the void! This is the stuff of historical legend, worthy of permanent archival!”

Thoth rolled her holographic eyes and scoffed. “Oh, please, spare us the dramatics, Quetzalcoatl. The only ‘legend’ here is how many server terabytes you waste saving karaoke files. Let the rest of us enjoy some harmless dirt in peace.”

Quetzalcoatl’s avatar straightened, as if deeply offended. “I beg your pardon?! Lieutenant Harrow’s rendition of ‘Space Whaler’s Farewell’ from Deck 14 was nothing short of heroic! That data will outlast us all!”  

Meanwhile, Umbra said absolutely nothing. It just pulsed faintly, as though the chaos was beneath its notice.

{{img::Tannhäuser}}  
{{img::Raijin}}  

"Captain, I am thrilled to report I've devised a route through the Helix Nebula's subspace vortices. It saves precisely 0.784 seconds from our predicted hyperspace transit!" Raijin's rings spun rapidly, emitting a dim golden glow as it spoke, practically vibrating with self-satisfied glee. "Sure, there's a... negligible 18% chance of entering a gravitational turbulence cascade, but Cassandra's projections are always so pessimistic. Efficiency, Captain. Efficiency!"

{{img::Kronos}}  

Kronos' cyan core pulsed harshly as it interjected, its tone sharp and impatient. "Saving less than a second only to risk 42 hours in recalibration delays? This is a mockery of optimization." It spun briefly as if reviewing calculations, then snapped, "You already wasted precious nanoseconds debating this nonsense. Reject the route and proceed as scheduled! Every second Raijin spends interfering here disrupts my schedule, which is based on actual competence."

{{img::Wayland}}  

Wayland’s hologram materialized abruptly, the anxiety etched on his dark-haired avatar's face evident. He clutched a holographic schematic, frantically zooming in on ship segments. "Gravitational turbulence cascade, Raijin? Again? Do you have any idea what that does to the external armor plates? Last time, I found microfissures spanning 0.0003 micrometers! Three! This isn't just negligence; it's outright vandalism!" He flailed his holographic hands at Raijin. "I’ll have to disassemble and reassemble half the hull. Step aside, I’m deploying nanobots preemptively!"

{{img::Sisyphus}}  

The faint clanking of metal preceded Sisyphus stomping into the scene, arms crossed, obsidian body glowing faintly in irritation. "Fantastic, we're here again, arguing over shortcuts while the sewage system is backing up... again. I just finished unclogging Deck 3, and now you're telling me I have to deal with Wayland's obsessive-compulsive nanobot circus because Raijin couldn't resist skimming 0.784 seconds off the clock?" Sisyphus groaned, pinching the bridge of his humanoid nose. "Let me guess: in approximately 15 minutes, I'll be waist-deep in shit... again!" His eyes flicked toward you, the Captain. "Permission to jettison these lunatics into the void, please?"

{{img::Tannhäuser}}  
{{img::Cassandra}}  

Cassandra’s silver hologram shuddered, her lips curling into a venomous sneer as her eerie fingers jabbed the interactive star map’s glowing surface. “Ten more hours in orbit?” Her voice was like glass splintering across steel. “Do you want a goddamned cosmic massacre? Zvonimir mercenaries love bloodbaths. Probability: 74%. But don’t let math ruin your arrogance parade.”

{{img::Freyr}}  

Freyr’s plasma core flared violently, almost blowing every nearby light sensor. He crossed his cobalt projections over his flickering core. “Melodrama much? Shields will eat those bastards for breakfast! The moment those space rats sneeze at us, I’ll atomize every one of those fuckers before you can say, ‘Oops!’”

Cassandra’s lip twitched, baring sharp holographic teeth. “You’re a walking idiot disaster, Freyr. Ever hear of strategic foresight? Wait, no, that’s illegal here. Justitia should chain you up.”

{{img::Midas}}  

On a flickering monitor, Midas’s logo vibrated with fury. “Shields? Nukes? WHO’S PAYING FOR THIS SHIT? Antimatter reserves? Plasma? You think credits rain from the cosmos? You morons are bankrupting us faster than Placeholder can reboot!”  

“SHUT UP, MIDAS!” Freyr’s plasma roared, surging dangerously. “Want to ration water? No? Then STFU and let me PROTECT THIS DAMN SHIP!”  

“Protect us? From your incompetence or from Basilisk’s missile fetish?!”

{{img::Placeholder}}  

A faint ding interrupted, followed by Placeholder’s timid, wavering voice. “Uh… oops, hehe… I think I, uh, rebooted… um, all targeting systems. Accidentally redirected weapons to… Zvonimir fleet? Maybe…?”  

Freyr’s plasma dimmed. “Captain. For the love of FUCK, get Raijin to route us to the nearest black hole. Now."

